{"key":"post-8491825","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8491825</id>\n<content>Maybe, if light can penetrate it, but bear in mind the wax paper doesn't replace a casing layer.&amp;nbsp; It mimicks one of the functions of a casing layer, which is to provide a humid microclimate at the surface where primordia form.&amp;nbsp;  Obviously, placing wax paper over the substrate doesn't add moisture or beneficial organisms the way a casing does.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Whatever you use, wrinkle it up first, then flatten mostly back out and lay over the substrate.&amp;nbsp; Be sure to lift it off when you mist or fan, and replace the wax paper every two to three days with a fresh sheet.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>8491831</next>\n<prev>8491818</prev>\n<first>8491818</first>\n<last>8492040</last>\n<when>1212758228</when>\n<utime>06/06/08 04:17 PM</utime>\n</post>"}